default of 
defaultthe Government of Wales Bill in 2006. You have reiterated your opposition to the ban. Can you remind the Committee why you have taken such a strong stance against the ban?
defaultProfessor Scullydefault: A
defaults I articulated in the written evidence that I submitted, the arguments against dual candidacy are flawed 
defaultboth 
defaultin principle and have problematic practical implications. I know some people feel very strongly against dual candidacy and I do not challenge the sincerity of their views, but I do believe that they are based on a misunderstanding of the nature of the electoral system that was introduced for Assembly elections. In particular, the argument is made that defeated candidates at the constituency level have b
defaulteen rejected by the electorate and, t
defaultherefore, they should no
defaultt be able to enter the Assembly. B
defaultut the pr
defaultoportional variant
default of AMS that we use for Assembly elections that is used in quite a few other countries around the world now is a voting system whereby parties
default,
default through the list seats
default,
default are compensated if they have been relatively unsuccessful in the constituencies. Parties who have been, in a sense, if you want to put it like that, rej
defaultected at the constituency level
default still 
defaultget some representation in the C
defaulthamber
default,
default and it is difficult to see a strong principled reason why what applies to parties should not also apply to individual candidates. 
defaultThe other reasons why I am opposed to a ban on dual candidacy 
defaultare
default, first, it creates potentially perverse incentives, which I do not think legislation ought to
default do. For instance, if you have 
defaultseparate constituency and list
default 
defaultgroups of candidates
default, 
defaultthe list ones then effectively acquire an incentive for their party
default’
defaults c
defaultonstituency candidates to lose—an
defaultd
default,
default indeed
default,
default one or two people here know about that directly
default. That is not 
defaulta sensible sort of incentive to build into a system. Also for the voters, if you particula
defaultrly favour a list candidate now,
default you maybe would want to vote against that party at the constituency level. 
defaultBut I think there is a third reason 
defaultthat
default is specific to 
defaultWales
default. Havi
defaultng a very small Assembly of 60 M
defaultembers, various people, including my colleague here, have argued 
defaultthat 
defaultthat is insufficient. Having such a small body, we need to do everything possible to maximise the quality of the representation within that body
